body.p:
The two reports that OIG profiled in the congressional testimony were part of a “large body of work including audits, investigations, inspections, and congressional testimony” (
Medicare: Home Health Care, 1997
). Over a period of 5 years in the 1990s, OIG evaluation staff had produced 14 reports on home health care issues, supplemented by audits, investigations, and another body of work by the U.S. General Accounting Office (GAO; now known as the General Accountability Office).

sec.p:
The findings of the second of the two reports that were summarized in the testimony showed that one quarter of home health care agencies were designated as “problem providers,” due, among other infractions, to filing for coverage for unallowed costs, filing claims that were deemed unauditable, not filing in a timely manner, submitting claims for medically unnecessary services or for services not rendered, or showing deficiencies in Medicare certification. Digging deeper, the OIG found some characteristics that the problem agencies had in common. First, their costs were higher; they tended to “be newer to the Medicare program, for-profit, provide more visits per patient, receive higher average reimbursement per patient and serve more chronic patients than other agencies” (
Medicare: Home Health Care, 1997
). The second characteristic was agency “owners with questionable backgrounds”—that is, with little or no health care experience or with financial issues such as previous bankruptcies, loan defaults, failure to pay taxes, or criminal records. Third, the problem agencies tended to be family-owned small corporations, often employing relatives who sometimes did little home health care work.
